    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n\r\nThe old `{runtime}/provider/*` pattern should be deprecated because:\r\n\r\n- Since Lua was introduced, it's now unnecessary because Lua monkey-patching works just as well.\r\n- Lua monkey-patching is more flexible because it allows stacking or \"inheritance\". The old \"provider\" pattern could not be \"stacked\": if you override `clipboard.vim` you can't re-use the builtin functionality, you must reimplement the entire thing.\r\n    -  Plus potential [future enhancements](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/22598)\r\n\r\nSo the \"provider\" pattern  is an unnecessary concept that adds cognitive overhead for Nvim users.\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\n- Move all the old providers to ~~vim.ui~~ `vim.os` (~~vim.ui is probably a fine place for all providers to live~~ (after more thought, `vim.ui` is probably too confusing to overload for this purpose; introduce `vim.os` instead for clipboard/etc.)).\r\n- Remove support for the old `{runtime}/provider/*` concept, and related documentation.\r\n    - For back-compat, it's probably not too difficult to shim the old `provider#clipboard#Call()` to the new module.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I agree with the main idea and point made here, i.e. to deprecate all the `*/provider/*` pattern. See: [`:help dev-provider`](https://neovim.io/doc/user/develop.html#dev-provider). I think Justin was mainly thinking of clipboard. Existing providers at the moment are rplugins (python, node, perl, ruby) and clipboard:\r\n\r\n- Clipboard is a member that belongs to `vim.ui` (as osc52 already does), see `vim.ui.clipboard`\r\n- But rplugins were called providers because they *provide* `providers#{lang}#Call()` to be called from C. Module-wise, they are about RPC support rather than UI, so `vim.ui` wouldn't be a good choice. I can suggest: `vim.remote` (but we may want to distinguish this from #21635), `vim.rpc`, etc.",
