        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> OTOH, they also provide API, so it would be a stretch...\r\n\r\nRight. we have `pyeval()` a la `luaeval()`, etc. Even `:python`, `:pydo`, etc. can be seen as for scripting. The concern of \"rplugin providers\" is too general and wide. If `:pydo`, etc. were about user interface then all other core features (buffers, windows, treesitter, etc.) would also concerning UIs too, after all. Some mid-level utilities and APIs such as notifications, prompts (e.g. `vim.ui.select()`), pop-up (floating windows) as a core util #25514, etc. are directly concerning user interfaces though.\r\n\r\nI think a better categorization can focus on their remote/RPC nature (their implementation and protocol) or external Language support for scripting, rather than on their function, i.e., what they are for (remote \"plugins\", eventually, for better UI/UX).",
